00:25:25,232 --> 00:25:27,752
So where exactly
are we right now?

499
00:25:27,792 --> 00:25:32,167
On the day that General Motors
declared Chapter 11 bankruptcy,

500
00:25:32,208 --> 00:25:35,502
l went with my dad to visit
the AC Spark Plug plant

501
00:25:35,536 --> 00:25:38,022
where he had worked
for over 30 years.

502
00:25:38,064 --> 00:25:41,576
- So you worked actually right here.
- You'd have to go--

503
00:25:41,615 --> 00:25:45,259
they had a ramp that took you
up over that, just beyond that...

504
00:25:45,295 --> 00:25:46,757
- Just beyond that space there?
- Yeah.

505
00:25:46,798 --> 00:25:48,708
- And then the factory was all over there?
- Yeah.

506
00:25:48,750 --> 00:25:51,052
Moore: The whole complex
is, like, two miles long.

507
00:25:51,086 --> 00:25:53,324
l remember Mom bringing
us kids in to pick you up.

508
00:25:53,358 --> 00:25:55,181
- 2:30 every day.
- Yeah, uh-huh.

509
00:25:55,214 --> 00:25:58,116
You'd walk out of there,
right over in there in fact.

510
00:25:58,159 --> 00:26:00,046
And we'd be waiting
in the car for you

511
00:26:00,078 --> 00:26:02,467
and we'd see you
come down the ramp.

512
00:26:02,509 --> 00:26:05,957
We got real excited
every time we saw you.

513
00:26:05,997 --> 00:26:08,385
l was there 33 1/2 years.

514
00:26:08,429 --> 00:26:10,403
- 33 1/2 years?
- Uh-huh.

515
00:26:10,444 --> 00:26:13,127
Moore: What's your best memory here,
being here, working here?

516
00:26:13,165 --> 00:26:16,199
My best memory?
l think the people.

517
00:26:16,237 --> 00:26:18,146
They were a really good bunch.

518
00:26:18,189 --> 00:26:20,938
- You liked the crowd you worked with?
- Yeah.

519
00:26:20,972 --> 00:26:24,104
Frank Moore:
A good place to work. l enjoyed it.

520
00:26:24,140 --> 00:26:26,888
But l'm sorry to see it go.

521
00:26:34,186 --> 00:26:36,805
Moore:
Shortly before Christmas 2008,

522
00:26:36,843 --> 00:26:39,843
Republic Windows & Doors
in Chicago, lllinois,

523
00:26:39,883 --> 00:26:42,981
abruptly fired
its entire unionized workforce

524
00:26:43,019 --> 00:26:45,953
of over 250 people.

525
00:26:45,994 --> 00:26:49,310
They were given
only three days' notice.

526
00:26:49,354 --> 00:26:51,328
Bank of America
would no longer provide

527
00:26:51,369 --> 00:26:53,474
a line of credit to the company,

528
00:26:53,513 --> 00:26:57,442
and so the workers were not paid
the money owed to them.

529
00:26:57,480 --> 00:27:00,163
Man #1 : My life revolves
around this job.

530
00:27:00,201 --> 00:27:04,194
l live according to my obligation
to my job, you know?

531
00:27:04,232 --> 00:27:08,127
And it's not just me,
it's all of the workers here.

532
00:27:08,169 --> 00:27:10,852
We go above and beyond

533
00:27:10,888 --> 00:27:13,375
the call of duty for Republic.

534
00:27:13,415 --> 00:27:16,034
And at the end,

535
00:27:16,071 --> 00:27:18,788
Republic cares nothing for us.

536
00:27:20,551 --> 00:27:23,398
Man #2: We found out that
they're gonna shut the plant on Tuesday.

537
00:27:23,432 --> 00:27:26,529
We don't deserve what
they're doing to us, you know?

538
00:27:26,567 --> 00:27:29,730
lt really hurts because,
like l said,

539
00:27:29,767 --> 00:27:31,653
this is my second family.

540
00:27:31,686 --> 00:27:34,173
So it was-- it really hurts.
lt really hurts.

541
00:27:34,213 --> 00:27:37,955
l'm gonna miss
all of them, you know?

542
00:27:37,990 --> 00:27:40,837
l'm gonna miss them
and l don't think

543
00:27:40,871 --> 00:27:43,106
anybody on this planet

544
00:27:43,142 --> 00:27:46,240
deserves what they've done to us.

545
00:27:53,413 --> 00:27:55,386
Moore: Scenes like this
were being repeated

546
00:27:55,429 --> 00:27:59,323
all over the country,
and no one seemed to mind.

547
00:27:59,365 --> 00:28:01,666
Zambezi, Zambezi

548
00:28:01,700 --> 00:28:04,700
-  Zambezi, Zam.
- Woman: Whoo!

549
00:28:04,740 --> 00:28:08,449
Moore: The president was enjoying
his final year in office.

550
00:28:08,483 --> 00:28:10,688
But as the economy
started to fall apart,

551
00:28:10,723 --> 00:28:14,684
he decided it was time
to roll out the C word.

552
00:28:14,723 --> 00:28:17,625
Capitalism is the best system
ever devised.

553
00:28:17,666 --> 00:28:19,009
Moore:
Huh. Really?

554
00:28:19,042 --> 00:28:22,173
Voices from the left and right
are equating the free enterprise system

555
00:28:22,211 --> 00:28:25,722
with greed and exploitation
and failure.

556
00:28:25,762 --> 00:28:27,672
Moore:
Hmm, greed,

557
00:28:27,713 --> 00:28:30,747
exploitation, failure?

558
00:28:30,787 --> 00:28:32,248
Go on, l'm listening.

559
00:28:32,289 --> 00:28:36,960
Capitalism offers people
the freedom to choose

560
00:28:36,993 --> 00:28:39,449
where they work
and what they do...

561
00:28:39,489 --> 00:28:42,075
Reporter: Pat Andrews
has been looking for work.

562
00:28:42,113 --> 00:28:45,822
Every morning she scans
the classifieds in vain.

563
00:28:45,856 --> 00:28:47,547
There isn't anything in here.

564
00:28:47,585 --> 00:28:50,398
l'm not gonna be a gentleman's club
hired dancer either.

565
00:28:51,681 --> 00:28:55,028
...the opportunity to buy
or sell products they want.

566
00:28:55,072 --> 00:28:56,926
Reporter: Tom Rendon
has avoided layoffs

567
00:28:56,961 --> 00:28:59,512
at his sign company
in Stockton, California,

568
00:28:59,551 --> 00:29:01,374
all because this one word
now makes up

569
00:29:01,406 --> 00:29:03,382
for half his business.

570
00:29:03,423 --> 00:29:06,838
lf you seek social justice
and human dignity,

571
00:29:06,878 --> 00:29:10,556
the free market system
is the way to go.

572
00:29:10,590 --> 00:29:12,217
( applause )

573
00:29:13,310 --> 00:29:16,310
Moore: And for those seeking
justice in Pennsylvania,

574
00:29:16,351 --> 00:29:20,093
free enterprise
was definitely the way to go.

575
00:29:23,453 --> 00:29:25,047
Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania,

576
00:29:25,086 --> 00:29:27,157
has one of the highest rates
in the state

577
00:29:27,198 --> 00:29:30,678
of young people locked up
in the juvenile home.

578
00:29:30,717 --> 00:29:32,952
Perhaps it's because
the good people here

579
00:29:32,989 --> 00:29:35,258
employ the practices
of capitalism

580
00:29:35,292 --> 00:29:38,392
in dealing with
their wayward youth.

581
00:29:38,429 --> 00:29:41,211
The county hired a private
profit-making corporation

582
00:29:41,244 --> 00:29:45,204
with a sweet-sounding name,
PA Child Care.

583
00:29:46,395 --> 00:29:49,211
lt was owned and run
by two businessmen,

584
00:29:49,243 --> 00:29:53,717
one of whom was Robert Powell,
an attorney and entrepreneur.

585
00:29:53,755 --> 00:29:55,609
His good friend Judge Conahan

586
00:29:55,644 --> 00:29:57,912
closed down
the public juvenile home

587
00:29:57,947 --> 00:29:59,801
and then got
PA Child Care to build

588
00:29:59,835 --> 00:30:02,867
an $8 million
privately-owned facility

589
00:30:02,906 --> 00:30:04,729
and charge it back to the county

590
00:30:04,761 --> 00:30:07,347
for a mere $58 million lease.

591
00:30:09,210 --> 00:30:12,690
Let's meet some of Wilkes-Barre's
juvenile delinquents.

592
00:30:12,730 --> 00:30:14,933
Magee smoked pot
at a high school party.

593
00:30:14,970 --> 00:30:18,067
l was very rebellious
when l was at this age.

594
00:30:18,105 --> 00:30:20,788
Moore: Matt, he got into
an argument at the dinner table.

595
00:30:20,826 --> 00:30:23,378
l threw a piece of meat,
as in steak,

596
00:30:23,416 --> 00:30:25,784
cooked dinner,
at my mother's boyfriend.

597
00:30:25,817 --> 00:30:28,086
Moore: Jamie got in a fight
at a shopping mall

598
00:30:28,121 --> 00:30:29,330
with her best friend.

599
00:30:29,367 --> 00:30:32,663
l just figured, you know, we just weren't
gonna be friends anymore.

600
00:30:32,697 --> 00:30:35,117
Moore: And Hillary made
a MySpace page

601
00:30:35,161 --> 00:30:37,232
making fun
of her assistant principal

602
00:30:37,271 --> 00:30:39,661
for being strict and having
no sense of humor.

603
00:30:39,703 --> 00:30:42,999
And it said some pretty silly,
like, 14-year-old-girl stuff.

604
00:30:43,031 --> 00:30:46,609
Moore: Her assistant principal
called the police.

605
00:30:46,646 --> 00:30:50,770
They all appeared before
kindly Judge Mark Ciavarella.

606
00:30:50,807 --> 00:30:53,424
These kids were about
to get their first lesson

607
00:30:53,462 --> 00:30:55,351
in American capitalism:

608
00:30:55,383 --> 00:30:59,987
time is money, lots of money.

609
00:31:00,022 --> 00:31:03,185
l went in front of the court,
in front of Mr. Ciavarella,

610
00:31:03,221 --> 00:31:04,944
and l wasn't even in front of him
for four minutes.

611
00:31:04,981 --> 00:31:06,990
l was only in front of him
for, like, two minutes.

612
00:31:07,029 --> 00:31:10,509
Hillary: The first thing that
Judge Ciavarella said to me was,

613
00:31:10,548 --> 00:31:13,298
''What makes you think
you can do this kind of crap?''

614
00:31:13,333 --> 00:31:15,666
l'm sure he knew in his mind
when l walked in

615
00:31:15,701 --> 00:31:17,391
that he was locking this kid up
no matter what.

616
00:31:17,429 --> 00:31:18,673
He didn't even look at me.

617
00:31:18,709 --> 00:31:21,556
Once l entered the courtroom,
l didn't have any chance.

618
00:31:21,588 --> 00:31:23,759
There was about six kids
who went in front of me.

619
00:31:23,796 --> 00:31:25,738
Every single kid who went
in front of Ciavarella,

620
00:31:25,779 --> 00:31:29,009
for all different reasons--
some minor, some serious--

621
00:31:29,044 --> 00:31:30,669
got sent away.

622
00:31:30,708 --> 00:31:34,449
Moore: Although Wilkes-Barre is located
in the United States of America,

623
00:31:34,483 --> 00:31:38,444
here capitalism
trumped democracy.

624
00:31:38,482 --> 00:31:41,580
Robert Powell, one of the owners
of PA Child Care,

625
00:31:41,618 --> 00:31:45,840
cut a business deal with Judge Conahan
and Judge Ciavarella.

626
00:31:45,875 --> 00:31:49,170
Judge Ciavarella then stepped up
his conviction rates.

627
00:31:49,201 --> 00:31:50,859
Many of these kids
were funneled

628
00:31:50,898 --> 00:31:55,470
into PA Child Care's
for-profit juvenile facility.

629
00:31:55,506 --> 00:31:56,847
And for their troubles,

630
00:31:56,882 --> 00:32:00,906
the judges received
over $2.6 million

631
00:32:00,945 --> 00:32:04,741
while the owners of PA Child Care
received tens of millions

632
00:32:04,785 --> 00:32:07,272
of taxpayer dollars
from the county.

633
00:32:07,313 --> 00:32:10,313
And where did Powell go
to enjoy all that money?

634
00:32:10,353 --> 00:32:12,458
On his private plane

635
00:32:12,496 --> 00:32:15,431
and his yacht,
the ''Reel Justice.''

636
00:32:17,039 --> 00:32:21,741
6,500 children
were unjustly convicted.

637
00:32:21,776 --> 00:32:25,038
lt was good business
while it lasted.

638
00:32:26,126 --> 00:32:28,875
Reporter #1 : Two Luzerne County
judges in big trouble with the law.

639
00:32:28,911 --> 00:32:29,858
They're going to jail.

640
00:32:29,903 --> 00:32:31,278
Reporter #2:
Some kids were locked up

641
00:32:31,310 --> 00:32:35,402
even when probation officers
objected to detention.

642
00:32:35,439 --> 00:32:38,307
ln there you lose track of time
and you lose track of the date.

643
00:32:38,349 --> 00:32:39,528
l was barely keeping track.

644
00:32:39,566 --> 00:32:42,566
lt was supposed to be, like--
l believe it was, like, two months.

645
00:32:42,605 --> 00:32:44,907
And it went from two months
to nine months.

646
00:32:44,942 --> 00:32:47,527
He said originally
three to six months,

647
00:32:47,566 --> 00:32:51,394
but somehow l ended up
being there 11 1/2 months

648
00:32:51,436 --> 00:32:54,153
and l never went back
in front of the judge at all

649
00:32:54,189 --> 00:32:55,750
for him to give me extensions.

650
00:32:55,788 --> 00:32:57,511
Moore:
Not only did PA Child Care

651
00:32:57,548 --> 00:33:00,265
pay off the judges
to fill their cells,

652
00:33:00,300 --> 00:33:02,854
but their employees were the ones
who got to decide

653
00:33:02,893 --> 00:33:06,153
when a child had
enough rehabilitation.

654
00:33:06,188 --> 00:33:09,384
But that makes sense,
because any time a governmental unit

655
00:33:09,421 --> 00:33:11,875
turns over to
a profit-making corporation

656
00:33:11,915 --> 00:33:14,217
the duties it should be performing,

657
00:33:14,251 --> 00:33:16,193
what do you expect to happen?

658
00:33:16,236 --> 00:33:18,722
Matt: lt makes me feel like
an item that they just used

659
00:33:18,763 --> 00:33:21,065
to just get money
and then tossed me aside.

660
00:33:21,098 --> 00:33:25,375
l'm just trying
to work on my flying

661
00:33:25,419 --> 00:33:27,523
and just trying to prepare
for my future

662
00:33:27,561 --> 00:33:30,661
so l can put this all behind me,
finally be done with all this.

663
00:33:30,698 --> 00:33:33,065
During the whole trial
l wasn't in control at all,

664
00:33:33,097 --> 00:33:35,432
but with flying it's only me.

665
00:33:35,465 --> 00:33:37,833
lt's just that l just get
to do everything by myself.

666
00:33:37,865 --> 00:33:39,807
l'm the only one on the control.

667
00:33:39,848 --> 00:33:41,605
Moore:
Matt loves to fly

668
00:33:41,642 --> 00:33:44,772
and hopes to become
a pilot someday.

669
00:33:44,808 --> 00:33:47,328
lf he does,
he'll get his second lesson

670
00:33:47,368 --> 00:33:49,855
in capitalism:

671
00:33:49,896 --> 00:33:52,798
that in America,
sometimes you're better off

672
00:33:52,840 --> 00:33:55,176
working at Mickey D's.

673
00:33:55,176 --> 00:33:57,632
- ( applause, cheering )
- Remember Sully?

674
00:33:57,672 --> 00:33:58,948
Captain Sullenberger,

675
00:33:58,983 --> 00:34:01,885
who safely landed an airbus
in the Hudson River

676
00:34:01,928 --> 00:34:04,829
- saving the lives of 150 passengers?
- ( patriotic music playing )

677
00:34:04,872 --> 00:34:07,621
- Man: A true American hero.
- ( applause )

678
00:34:10,630 --> 00:34:13,413
Moore: He met the mayor.
He went to the State of the Union.

679
00:34:13,447 --> 00:34:16,032
Heck, he even went
to the Super Bowl.

680
00:34:16,070 --> 00:34:18,208
And then he went to Congress.

681
00:34:18,246 --> 00:34:21,181
Sullenberger:
Flying has been my lifelong passion.

682
00:34:21,222 --> 00:34:23,293
But while l love my profession,

683
00:34:23,335 --> 00:34:25,920
l do not like
what has happened to it.

684
00:34:25,958 --> 00:34:27,965
- ( music halts )
- lt is my personal experience

685
00:34:28,005 --> 00:34:31,072
that my decision to remain
in the profession l love

686
00:34:31,110 --> 00:34:35,550
has come at a great financial cost
to me and to my family.

687
00:34:35,588 --> 00:34:37,760
My pay has been cut 40%.

688
00:34:37,797 --> 00:34:41,309
My pension, like most airline pensions,
has been terminated.

689
00:34:41,349 --> 00:34:44,731
So please do not think l exaggerate
when l say that l do not know

690
00:34:44,771 --> 00:34:47,936
a single professional airline pilot
who wants his or her children

691
00:34:47,972 --> 00:34:49,498
to follow in their footsteps.

692
00:34:49,539 --> 00:34:52,157
Moore: Whoa, you cleared
the room with that one, Sully.

693
00:34:52,195 --> 00:34:54,398
l don't think the congressmen
wanted to hear that stuff.

694
00:34:54,436 --> 00:34:57,250
- They like you as a hero.
- The current experience...

695
00:34:57,284 --> 00:34:59,672
( patriotic music over dialogue )

696
00:35:11,233 --> 00:35:13,208
Moore: What was
your starting pay as a pilot?

697
00:35:13,251 --> 00:35:15,454
l made $19,000 the first year.

698
00:35:15,489 --> 00:35:18,806
l was bumped up to about 22,000
or 23,000 the second year.

699
00:35:18,849 --> 00:35:21,369
Last year, gross pay

700
00:35:21,409 --> 00:35:23,744
l made $17,600.

701
00:35:23,777 --> 00:35:26,264
There's a joke in the airline
when we get our wings pinned on us

702
00:35:26,304 --> 00:35:29,621
as new-hire airline pilots
that the company just kinda says,

703
00:35:29,664 --> 00:35:32,315
''Hey, don't apply for food stamps
in your uniform.''

704
00:35:32,351 --> 00:35:35,101
Moore: l don't know about you,
but l want the pilot

705
00:35:35,135 --> 00:35:38,780
who's got me 30,000 feet up in the air
to be paid really well

706
00:35:38,815 --> 00:35:41,750
and not sitting up in the cockpit
digging through the pilot's seat

707
00:35:41,791 --> 00:35:43,702
looking for loose change.

708
00:35:43,744 --> 00:35:45,630
There was a period
of about four months

709
00:35:45,664 --> 00:35:48,313
where l was on food stamps.

710
00:35:48,351 --> 00:35:49,780
- You were on food stamps?
- Yes.

711
00:35:49,824 --> 00:35:52,474
- And you were still flying the plane?
- Yes.

712
00:35:52,510 --> 00:35:54,780
With my--
with my food stamp card.

713
00:35:54,815 --> 00:35:57,465
The lady l talked to
in the food stamp office,

714
00:35:57,503 --> 00:36:00,318
when l told her l was a pilot,
she didn't bat an eye,

715
00:36:00,349 --> 00:36:02,586
but she didn't--
l knew she didn't believe me.

716
00:36:02,621 --> 00:36:05,141
Moore: How have you gotten by?
How have you been able to afford things?

717
00:36:05,181 --> 00:36:07,670
Relying on credit cards
to buy the groceries at times

718
00:36:07,710 --> 00:36:09,367
- when l wasn't on food stamps.
- Oh, really?

719
00:36:09,405 --> 00:36:11,608
l have about $10,000
in credit card debt

720
00:36:11,646 --> 00:36:13,554
just on the necessities,

721
00:36:13,597 --> 00:36:16,052
not on the big-screen TV
and the stereo.

722
00:36:16,094 --> 00:36:19,159
Moore: You're using it
to buy your groceries and get by.

723
00:36:19,197 --> 00:36:21,050
- Yes.
- Do you have any student loan debt?

724
00:36:21,085 --> 00:36:22,710
- Yes.
- How much?

725
00:36:22,748 --> 00:36:24,242
Mine is about 80,000.

726
00:36:24,284 --> 00:36:27,545
- l took out $100,000.
- Moore: Student loans?

727
00:36:27,579 --> 00:36:30,329
And by the time l pay it back,
at this rate,

728
00:36:30,364 --> 00:36:32,632
it'll probably cost me well over
a half a million with interest

729
00:36:32,668 --> 00:36:35,123
and fees and penalties.

730
00:36:35,164 --> 00:36:37,302
lt's something that l don't--
l don't like to spend a lot of time

731
00:36:37,338 --> 00:36:38,965
thinking about
because it's abysmal.

732
00:36:39,003 --> 00:36:41,369
lt's one way that l get down
really quickly

733
00:36:41,403 --> 00:36:42,996
about my chosen career field

734
00:36:43,034 --> 00:36:45,369
is to think about how much l owe
and how little l make.

735
00:36:45,402 --> 00:36:48,184
Moore: Have you had to work
a second job to make ends meet?

736
00:36:48,219 --> 00:36:50,487
l walk dogs on the side,

737
00:36:50,521 --> 00:36:53,588
l distribute MonaVie Juice.

738
00:36:53,626 --> 00:36:56,757
l have known pilots
to donate plasma

739
00:36:56,793 --> 00:36:58,550
for extra cash.

740
00:36:58,585 --> 00:37:01,335
- You mean they give blood?
- They-- well--

741
00:37:01,369 --> 00:37:03,889
So they can make extra money
even though they're flying an airplane?

742
00:37:03,929 --> 00:37:05,838
Yeah.
They donate their plasma.

743
00:37:05,880 --> 00:37:09,972
So they get the blood back,
but you can get paid for plasma.

744
00:37:10,007 --> 00:37:11,251
- ( chuckles )
- Oh, l see.

745
00:37:11,289 --> 00:37:13,012
They suck the blood out of you,
take the plasma...

746
00:37:13,047 --> 00:37:14,454
- Give you the blood back.
- ...give you the--

747
00:37:14,489 --> 00:37:16,277
Oh, well then,
not such a bad deal.

748
00:37:16,313 --> 00:37:19,661
The only reason people stay flying
is because they love it.

749
00:37:19,704 --> 00:37:21,492
And managements
take advantage of that.

750
00:37:21,527 --> 00:37:24,724
The airlines
have managed to farm out

751
00:37:24,760 --> 00:37:28,983
a lot of the flying to commuters

752
00:37:29,014 --> 00:37:32,081
in an effort to basically
bust the unions.

753
00:37:32,119 --> 00:37:34,126
You can't compete

754
00:37:34,166 --> 00:37:38,224
to a lower and lower level
every year

755
00:37:38,262 --> 00:37:40,563
without skimping
on safety somehow.

756
00:37:42,773 --> 00:37:47,378
Moore: At approximately 10:15 PM
on February 1 2, 2009,

757
00:37:47,414 --> 00:37:50,032
Continental connection flight 3407

758
00:37:50,070 --> 00:37:52,557
began its descent
to the airport in Buffalo.

759
00:37:52,597 --> 00:37:54,222
( sirens wailing )

760
00:37:54,262 --> 00:37:56,050
Man: Stand by, there's some
ground communication,

761
00:37:56,085 --> 00:37:57,907
either state police
or sheriff's department.

762
00:37:57,940 --> 00:37:59,567
We need to find out if anything
is on the ground.

763
00:37:59,605 --> 00:38:01,907
This aircraft was five miles out,
and all of a sudden

764
00:38:01,940 --> 00:38:03,697
we have no response
to that aircraft.

765
00:38:03,733 --> 00:38:06,601
All l could tell you is there was
an aircraft over the marker

766
00:38:06,643 --> 00:38:09,545
and we're not talking to them now.

767
00:38:09,588 --> 00:38:11,659
Moore:
No one survived the crash

768
00:38:11,699 --> 00:38:14,514
and 50 people lost their lives.

769
00:38:15,987 --> 00:38:19,119
The media focused
on the actions of the pilots.

770
00:38:19,155 --> 00:38:22,090
Reporter: Captain Marvin Renslow
and First Officer Shaw

771
00:38:22,130 --> 00:38:24,269
were chatting about their careers.

772
00:38:24,306 --> 00:38:26,576
Moore:
''Careers'' is a euphemism

773
00:38:26,610 --> 00:38:28,911
for what the pilots
were really talking about:

774
00:38:28,947 --> 00:38:32,907
how little they were paid
and how overworked they were.

775
00:38:32,945 --> 00:38:34,954
There would be
no discussion in the media

776
00:38:34,994 --> 00:38:37,164
about why we have
an economic system

777
00:38:37,202 --> 00:38:40,681
that allows a pilot to be paid less
than a manager at Taco Bell.

778
00:38:40,722 --> 00:38:42,063
Reporter:
First Officer Shaw

779
00:38:42,097 --> 00:38:45,577
made between
$16,000 and $20,000 a year

780
00:38:45,617 --> 00:38:49,032
and at one point
worked a second job.

781
00:38:49,072 --> 00:38:51,407
Moore: Her second job
had been waitressing

782
00:38:51,440 --> 00:38:53,349
at a coffee shop.

783
00:38:54,608 --> 00:38:57,990
How are these companies
able to get away with this?

784
00:38:58,032 --> 00:39:00,617
( laughs )
l guess that's the point of capitalism.

785
00:39:00,655 --> 00:39:03,306
lt allows you to get away
with anything,

786
00:39:03,344 --> 00:39:06,574
like making a profit
off the death of an employee.

787
00:39:08,079 --> 00:39:10,347
Sweetie, l can open it.
Let's try it with this.

788
00:39:10,382 --> 00:39:12,358
Moore:
This is lrma Johnson.

789
00:39:12,398 --> 00:39:15,246
lrma's husband Dan
worked in middle management

790
00:39:15,278 --> 00:39:17,351
at Amegy Bank in Houston, Texas.

791
00:39:17,391 --> 00:39:19,364
- Wanna try to spread it?
- No.

792
00:39:19,405 --> 00:39:21,827
Moore:
Dan recently died of cancer,

793
00:39:21,871 --> 00:39:25,929
leaving behind lrma
and their two sons.

794
00:39:25,965 --> 00:39:28,420
But unbeknownst to lrma,
Amegy had taken out

795
00:39:28,461 --> 00:39:32,257
a secret life insurance policy
on Dan's life.

796
00:39:32,302 --> 00:39:36,360
The bank generously named itself
as the beneficiary

797
00:39:36,396 --> 00:39:38,786
in the event of Dan's death.

798
00:39:38,829 --> 00:39:41,829
The insurance company
then accidentally informed lrma

799
00:39:41,869 --> 00:39:45,829
that Amegy Bank had received
a check for $1 1/2 million

800
00:39:45,869 --> 00:39:48,684
just weeks after Dan died.

801
00:39:48,715 --> 00:39:50,438
Thank you for helping.

802
00:39:50,476 --> 00:39:51,489
Johnson:
They never told me.

803
00:39:51,532 --> 00:39:54,914
l wanted to find out, well,
why did they purchase a policy for him?

804
00:39:54,956 --> 00:39:56,811
- Moore: You didn't know about it?
- No.

805
00:39:56,842 --> 00:40:00,356
And they named themselves
as the beneficiary.

806
00:40:00,394 --> 00:40:01,344
Yeah.

807
00:40:01,387 --> 00:40:03,458
Moore:
So your husband's death

808
00:40:03,500 --> 00:40:06,347
made them $1.5 million richer?

809
00:40:06,378 --> 00:40:08,550
Mm-hmm.

810
00:40:08,586 --> 00:40:11,969
l know it's not right
for them to try to profit

811
00:40:12,010 --> 00:40:14,344
from my husband's death.

812
00:40:14,378 --> 00:40:16,101
When l first realized
what was happening,

813
00:40:16,137 --> 00:40:20,032
l was in disbelief.

814
00:40:20,072 --> 00:40:22,690
- lt's hurtful.
- l'm so sorry.

815
00:40:24,106 --> 00:40:25,480
Um...

816
00:40:27,880 --> 00:40:31,329
it's hurtful and l wanted answers.

817
00:40:31,369 --> 00:40:33,922
Moore: lrma contacted
Michael D. Myers,

818
00:40:33,960 --> 00:40:36,349
a local attorney who had
already been looking into

819
00:40:36,391 --> 00:40:39,556
these kind of corporate
insurance policies on their employees.

820
00:40:40,903 --> 00:40:43,391
With the normal use of life insurance,
where you're guarding against

821
00:40:43,431 --> 00:40:47,806
the loss of a loved one
or a breadwinner of the family,

822
00:40:47,847 --> 00:40:52,070
you don't want that person to die.

823
00:40:52,103 --> 00:40:54,175
With these policies,
the companies that buy these

824
00:40:54,215 --> 00:40:56,003
want the employees to die

825
00:40:56,039 --> 00:40:58,625
in accordance
with the policy projections.

826
00:40:58,663 --> 00:41:02,405
You are more valuable dead
to a company than alive.

827
00:41:03,653 --> 00:41:07,003
American Greetings, RR Donnelly & Sons,
and Proctor & Gamble

828
00:41:07,045 --> 00:41:09,697
are all having problems
with mortality.

829
00:41:09,733 --> 00:41:12,123
These four combined programs
are running at 50%

830
00:41:12,164 --> 00:41:13,594
of expected mortality.

831
00:41:13,637 --> 00:41:16,952
These clients are acutely aware
of this problem.

832
00:41:16,998 --> 00:41:19,583
Basically here the broker
is complaining

833
00:41:19,621 --> 00:41:21,922
that not enough
employees are dying.

834
00:41:21,956 --> 00:41:25,503
And therefore the investment returns
are not matching the projections.

835
00:41:25,541 --> 00:41:27,875
The broker writes
that NCC is running

836
00:41:27,909 --> 00:41:30,494
at 78% of expected mortality.

837
00:41:30,532 --> 00:41:34,242
Okay, so 78% of the people
we expected to die died.

838
00:41:34,275 --> 00:41:37,375
But the problem with that
is three of them were suicides.

839
00:41:37,411 --> 00:41:39,452
And you can't count
on that every year.

840
00:41:39,492 --> 00:41:41,434
Moore: Can you think
of any other situation

841
00:41:41,474 --> 00:41:45,630
were you'd actually want
people to die?

842
00:41:45,666 --> 00:41:49,692
Combatants in war, l guess.

843
00:41:49,731 --> 00:41:53,375
Wow, when do you want
people to die?

844
00:41:53,409 --> 00:41:54,971
l-l don't know.

845
00:41:55,010 --> 00:41:58,653
War situations,
terrorism situations.

846
00:42:00,512 --> 00:42:03,099
Drug trials, perhaps.
l don't know.

847
00:42:03,137 --> 00:42:05,626
l don't know.
That's an odd question.

848
00:42:05,664 --> 00:42:08,762
Moore: l didn't understand
how any of this could be legal.

849
00:42:08,800 --> 00:42:11,518
After all, there's a reason
that there's a law

850
00:42:11,552 --> 00:42:15,775
prohibiting me from taking out
a fire insurance policy on your house

851
00:42:15,809 --> 00:42:19,867
because l have a vested interest
in your house burning down.

852
00:42:19,905 --> 00:42:22,903
Since Attorney Myers had been
researching this for years,

853
00:42:22,943 --> 00:42:24,918
l asked him which companies
were profiting

854
00:42:24,960 --> 00:42:26,684
from these insurance policies.

855
00:42:26,719 --> 00:42:28,094
l don't know,
you don't know,

856
00:42:28,128 --> 00:42:30,648
because there's no place
you can go and find out

857
00:42:30,686 --> 00:42:34,166
whether your company
is a purchaser

858
00:42:34,208 --> 00:42:36,411
- of these types of products.
- Which ones do you know?

859
00:42:36,447 --> 00:42:38,072
The ones that we know
that have slipped out are

860
00:42:38,110 --> 00:42:40,052
Bank of America, Citibank,

861
00:42:40,094 --> 00:42:43,257
Wal-Mart, Winn-Dixie,
Proctor & Gamble,

862
00:42:43,295 --> 00:42:45,333
McDonnell Douglas, Hershey,

863
00:42:45,375 --> 00:42:48,222
Nestle , AT&T,
Southwestern Bell,

864
00:42:48,255 --> 00:42:50,228
Ameritech, American Express--

865
00:42:50,269 --> 00:42:52,244
- This is blue chip you're talking about.
- Yeah.

866
00:42:52,286 --> 00:42:55,351
These aren't fly-by-night companies
trying to do a scam here

867
00:42:55,389 --> 00:42:57,461
so they can collect a check
if one of their employees dies.

868
00:42:57,501 --> 00:43:00,664
There are probably
several million Americans

869
00:43:00,701 --> 00:43:04,378
who are covered by one of these policies
or have been at some point.

870
00:43:04,413 --> 00:43:05,623
There's a lot of it out there.

871
00:43:05,661 --> 00:43:07,733
Moore:
This is Paul Smith.

872
00:43:07,771 --> 00:43:11,186
He used to be what is known
as a loyal employee.

873
00:43:11,228 --> 00:43:15,286
Smith: l worked for Wal-Mart
for 18 years and l gave them 110%.

874
00:43:15,324 --> 00:43:17,014
l mean, l loved that company.

875
00:43:17,052 --> 00:43:18,481
And as it turned out,
Wal-Mart took out

876
00:43:18,523 --> 00:43:21,458
over 350,000
life insurance policies

877
00:43:21,498 --> 00:43:23,539
on rank and file associates.

878
00:43:23,579 --> 00:43:24,724
These weren't executives.

879
00:43:24,762 --> 00:43:28,057
These were people like my wife,
a cake decorator for 18 months.

880
00:43:28,090 --> 00:43:31,538
That's the type of people they were taking
insurance policies out on.

881
00:43:31,579 --> 00:43:35,407
Moore: Paul's wife LaDonna
left her job at the Wal-Mart bakery

882
00:43:35,449 --> 00:43:38,132
so she could be a stay-at-home mom
for her two kids.

883
00:43:38,170 --> 00:43:41,204
Smith:
She had asthma real real bad.

884
00:43:41,242 --> 00:43:43,097
She went into
the emergency room one night

885
00:43:43,128 --> 00:43:45,016
and a nurse comes out and says,
''Are you Mr. Smith?''

886
00:43:45,048 --> 00:43:46,478
And l said, ''Yes.''

887
00:43:46,521 --> 00:43:50,416
And she said, ''We don't think
your wife's gonna make it.''

888
00:43:50,456 --> 00:43:52,344
Moore:
LaDonna slipped into a coma

889
00:43:52,376 --> 00:43:54,612
from which she would
never awaken.

890
00:43:54,648 --> 00:43:56,721
Her family rushed to the hospital,

891
00:43:56,760 --> 00:43:59,094
even though there was nothing
they could do to help.

892
00:43:59,128 --> 00:44:01,583
There was a wall here
and LaDonna's in the room

893
00:44:01,623 --> 00:44:02,998
on the other side of the wall.

894
00:44:03,032 --> 00:44:05,202
And Jessica kept saying,
''Where is she?''

895
00:44:05,239 --> 00:44:07,760
And l said, ''She's right on
the other side of that wall.''

896
00:44:07,800 --> 00:44:11,246
And Jessica said,
''Can we cut a hole in the wall

897
00:44:11,286 --> 00:44:13,675
so that we can see her?''

898
00:44:13,719 --> 00:44:15,661
And that just sticks with me.

899
00:44:15,702 --> 00:44:17,458
Do you remember that?

900
00:44:19,478 --> 00:44:23,668
Smith: We had to stay in there with her,
and so we'd write letters to her.

901
00:44:23,702 --> 00:44:27,978
''My dear wife, l miss you more
than any words can possibly say.

902
00:44:28,021 --> 00:44:29,516
You are my life.

903
00:44:29,557 --> 00:44:31,858
You always see beauty
in the simplest things.

904
00:44:31,893 --> 00:44:36,148
l've always admired you for that.
l wish l could have told you that more.

905
00:44:36,181 --> 00:44:38,351
l want you to come back
to me soon.

906
00:44:38,389 --> 00:44:41,259
l still have a lot left to learn
from you, baby doll.

907
00:44:41,300 --> 00:44:43,373
Your loving husband, Paul.''

908
00:44:45,237 --> 00:44:47,570
You okay, Wesley?

909
00:44:48,916 --> 00:44:51,567
She was 26 years old.

910
00:44:51,603 --> 00:44:54,418
LaDonna: You're silly.
You're silly.

911
00:44:54,452 --> 00:44:57,965
Myers: The younger a person is,
the higher the benefit is

912
00:44:58,003 --> 00:45:00,686
because they're expected
to live longer.

913
00:45:00,724 --> 00:45:02,829
Women are also expected
to live longer than men.

914
00:45:02,867 --> 00:45:05,713
So the most valuable employee
to the company

915
00:45:05,746 --> 00:45:08,528
if they're dead,
is a young woman.

916
00:45:08,563 --> 00:45:10,088
Moore:
LaDonna's death earned

917
00:45:10,130 --> 00:45:12,268
one of the richest corporations
in the world

918
00:45:12,306 --> 00:45:14,760
an extra $81,000.

919
00:45:14,802 --> 00:45:17,998
l was faced with over $100,000
worth of medical bills

920
00:45:18,034 --> 00:45:21,230
and a $6,000 funeral

921
00:45:21,266 --> 00:45:24,581
and Wal-Mart didn't offer a penny
to help with that.

922
00:45:24,625 --> 00:45:27,755
l did trust them.

923
00:45:27,793 --> 00:45:30,925
And never in a million years
would l have ever thought

924
00:45:30,960 --> 00:45:33,775
that somewhere
on a profit statement,

925
00:45:33,809 --> 00:45:36,677
''Dead associate, $81,000.''

926
00:45:36,721 --> 00:45:40,550
Wal-Mart doesn't care about you.

927
00:45:40,592 --> 00:45:42,347
When someone passes away,

928
00:45:42,384 --> 00:45:45,067
they shouldn't get
something out of it.

929
00:45:55,311 --> 00:45:57,699
Myers: The common denominator
to each form of coverage

930
00:45:57,742 --> 00:45:59,684
is that when the employee dies,

931
00:45:59,726 --> 00:46:02,826
the employer gets paid
the insurance benefits.

932
00:46:02,862 --> 00:46:05,896
They're often referred to
as ''dead peasant insurance.''

933
00:46:05,934 --> 00:46:09,349
Moore: Dead peasants?
Why'd they use such a creepy name?

934
00:46:09,389 --> 00:46:12,389
Myers: lt's very creepy.
l don't know what it means either.

935
00:46:12,429 --> 00:46:13,541
Dead is clear.

936
00:46:13,581 --> 00:46:16,199
That's the worker who's passed away,
so they're dead.

937
00:46:16,237 --> 00:46:18,572
Peasant, l don't know why
they chose that word.

938
00:46:18,605 --> 00:46:20,547
l don't know if it has
some historical significance

939
00:46:20,588 --> 00:46:23,458
or that's just the way they view
the relative value

940
00:46:23,501 --> 00:46:25,159
of the employees' lives.

941
00:46:25,197 --> 00:46:26,724
Dead peasants?

942
00:46:26,764 --> 00:46:28,804
Yeah, amongst themselves
that's what they call it.

943
00:46:30,315 --> 00:46:34,375
lt's insulting to refer
to my husband like that.

944
00:46:34,411 --> 00:46:36,353
( sniffles )

945
00:46:41,226 --> 00:46:42,721
Moore:
lt turned out that Amegy Bank

946
00:46:42,764 --> 00:46:45,349
had a second
dead peasant policy on Dan,

947
00:46:45,387 --> 00:46:49,215
bringing their total take
to nearly $5 million.

948
00:46:51,947 --> 00:46:52,907
- ls capitalism a sin?
- Father Dick Preston: Yes.

949
00:46:52,907 --> 00:46:54,760
- ls capitalism a sin?
- Father Dick Preston: Yes.

950
00:46:54,795 --> 00:46:57,250
Capitalism for me and for many of us

951
00:46:57,289 --> 00:47:00,485
at this present moment is an evil.

952
00:47:00,521 --> 00:47:04,132
lt's contrary to all that's good.
lt's contrary to the common good.

953
00:47:04,170 --> 00:47:06,307
lt's contrary to compassion.

954
00:47:06,344 --> 00:47:09,193
lt's contrary to
all of the major religions.

955
00:47:09,224 --> 00:47:13,119
Capitalism is precisely
what the holy books,

956
00:47:13,161 --> 00:47:17,632
our holy books in particular,
remind us is unjust

957
00:47:17,672 --> 00:47:20,519
and in some form and fashion,

958
00:47:20,552 --> 00:47:25,123
God will come down
and eradicate somehow.

959
00:47:25,159 --> 00:47:27,396
Moore:
This was Father Dick Preston,

960
00:47:27,431 --> 00:47:30,628
the priest from Flint
who married my wife and me.

961
00:47:30,664 --> 00:47:32,735
Preston:
Capitalism is wrong,

962
00:47:32,775 --> 00:47:36,353
and therefore
has to be eliminated.

963
00:47:36,391 --> 00:47:38,300
Moore:
Eliminated?

964
00:47:38,342 --> 00:47:40,253
That might be a little harsh,

965
00:47:40,295 --> 00:47:42,204
so l decided to go
and talk to the priest

966
00:47:42,246 --> 00:47:44,449
that married my sister
and brother-in-law.

967
00:47:44,485 --> 00:47:46,690
l'm sure he would have
a more balanced approach

968
00:47:46,726 --> 00:47:48,766
when it came to capitalism.

969
00:47:48,806 --> 00:47:52,581
lt is immoral, it is obscene,
it is outrageous.

970
00:47:52,614 --> 00:47:55,231
You know...

971
00:47:55,269 --> 00:47:57,505
it is really radical evil.

972
00:47:57,541 --> 00:47:59,744
lt's radically evil.

973
00:47:59,780 --> 00:48:03,163
Moore: Wow, does their boss know
that they're talking like this?

974
00:48:03,204 --> 00:48:06,106
l thought it best to go
and check this out with the bishop.

975
00:48:06,148 --> 00:48:08,320
Bishop Thomas Gumbleton:
The system doesn't seem to be

976
00:48:08,356 --> 00:48:11,967
providing for the well being
of all the people.

977
00:48:12,003 --> 00:48:14,786
And that's what makes it

978
00:48:14,820 --> 00:48:17,186
almost in its very nature

979
00:48:17,219 --> 00:48:20,994
something contrary
to Jesus who said,

980
00:48:21,027 --> 00:48:24,409
''Blessed are the poor,
woe to the rich.''

981
00:48:24,451 --> 00:48:27,516
That's right out
of St. Luke's gospel.

982
00:48:27,554 --> 00:48:29,759
Moore: How have we put up
with this system for so long?

983
00:48:29,795 --> 00:48:31,867
l mean, it's--
they talk about--

984
00:48:31,907 --> 00:48:36,097
The system has built into it
what we call propaganda.

985
00:48:36,130 --> 00:48:38,268
l'm in awe of propaganda--

986
00:48:38,306 --> 00:48:41,153
the ability to convince people

987
00:48:41,186 --> 00:48:44,001
who are victimized
by this very system

988
00:48:44,032 --> 00:48:46,880
to support the system
and see it as good.

989
00:48:46,913 --> 00:48:50,173
We know that American capitalism
is morally right

990
00:48:50,208 --> 00:48:52,280
because its chief elements--

991
00:48:52,320 --> 00:48:55,255
private ownership,
the profit motive

992
00:48:55,297 --> 00:48:58,199
and the competitive market--
are wholesome and good.

993
00:48:58,239 --> 00:49:01,403
They are compatible with God's laws
and the teachings of the Bible.

994
00:49:02,369 --> 00:49:04,190
Moore: For as long
as l can remember,

995
00:49:04,224 --> 00:49:07,672
l've been told that competition
and profit are good things.

996
00:49:07,711 --> 00:49:09,719
( distorted )
They are compatible with God's laws

997
00:49:09,759 --> 00:49:10,871
and the teachings of the Bible.

998
00:49:10,911 --> 00:49:14,106
Moore: And if increasing profits
means locking up a few kids

999
00:49:14,143 --> 00:49:16,184
or cashing in on the death
of an employee...

1000
00:49:16,222 --> 00:49:18,940
( distorted ) Compatible with God's laws
and the teachings of the Bible.

1001
00:49:18,974 --> 00:49:22,106
Moore: ...it is morally right to provide
for the stockholders.

1002
00:49:22,143 --> 00:49:24,378
( distorted )
They are compatible with God's laws

1003
00:49:24,414 --> 00:49:25,592
and the teachings of the Bible.

1004
00:49:25,630 --> 00:49:28,728
Moore:
Debt, eviction and exploitation.

1005
00:49:28,766 --> 00:49:32,081
( distorted )
God's laws and the teachings of the Bible.

1006
00:49:32,126 --> 00:49:34,940
Moore: What were we really
pledging our allegiance to?

1007
00:49:34,972 --> 00:49:37,788
( distorted )
The profit motive.

1008
00:49:37,822 --> 00:49:40,407
Moore: And so all good Americans
came to act as if they believed

1009
00:49:40,445 --> 00:49:43,478
our capitalist economic system
was compatible

1010
00:49:43,516 --> 00:49:45,753
with the teachings of the Bible.

1011
00:49:48,507 --> 00:49:51,378
( organ music playing )

1012
00:49:53,692 --> 00:49:57,369
When l was a kid,
l wanted to be a priest.

1013
00:49:57,403 --> 00:49:59,126
lt wasn't because
of the fancy getups

1014
00:49:59,163 --> 00:50:01,333
or the Knights of Columbus
escorts,

1015
00:50:01,371 --> 00:50:04,534
or even the groovy nuns
who were so good to me.

1016
00:50:05,530 --> 00:50:08,913
lt was because of the priests
who went on the march from Selma,

1017
00:50:08,954 --> 00:50:11,409
or tried to stop the war,

1018
00:50:11,451 --> 00:50:14,766
or devoted their lives to the poor.

1019
00:50:14,811 --> 00:50:18,606
They told me quite clearly
what Jesus said,

1020
00:50:18,650 --> 00:50:22,840
that the first shall be last
and the last shall be first;

1021
00:50:22,873 --> 00:50:25,458
That the rich man
will have a very hard time

1022
00:50:25,496 --> 00:50:27,472
getting into heaven;

1023
00:50:27,512 --> 00:50:31,190
That we will be judged by how
we treat the least among us;

1024
00:50:31,224 --> 00:50:33,746
And that there are no people
more important to God

1025
00:50:33,784 --> 00:50:36,206
than the poor.

1026
00:50:36,248 --> 00:50:38,670
Since that time,
it seems that Jesus got hijacked

1027
00:50:38,713 --> 00:50:41,559
by a lot of people who believe
that the son of God

1028
00:50:41,592 --> 00:50:45,782
was sent here to create
heaven on earth for the well-to-do.

1029
00:50:45,815 --> 00:50:47,920
l must have missed
that part of the Bible

1030
00:50:47,960 --> 00:50:51,123
where Jesus became a capitalist.

1031
00:50:55,255 --> 00:50:56,782
Man:
Please tell me, master,

1032
00:50:56,822 --> 00:50:59,474
what must l do
to have eternal life?

1033
00:50:59,510 --> 00:51:02,893
Go forth and maximize profits.

1034
00:51:04,663 --> 00:51:07,858
You say the Kingdom of Heaven
is at hand,

1035
00:51:07,893 --> 00:51:09,356
but when exactly will it come?

1036
00:51:09,398 --> 00:51:13,423
When you deregulate
the banking industry.

1037
00:51:13,461 --> 00:51:16,429
- ( voices overlapping )
- Help me.

1038
00:51:16,469 --> 00:51:18,891
l've been this way for 20 years.

1039
00:51:20,661 --> 00:51:24,010
l'm sorry, l cannot heal
your pre-existing condition.

1040
00:51:25,940 --> 00:51:27,534
He'll have to pay out of pocket.

1041
00:51:30,804 --> 00:51:33,193
Moore: Somehow, l don't think
Jesus came to earth

1042
00:51:33,235 --> 00:51:36,268
so he could ring the bell
at the New York Stock Exchange.

1043
00:51:36,307 --> 00:51:38,217
And yet,
from the very beginning,

1044
00:51:38,260 --> 00:51:40,976
the rich have claimed him
for their own.

1045
00:51:41,012 --> 00:51:44,655
When l'm on Wall Street
and l realize

1046
00:51:44,692 --> 00:51:48,652
that that's the very nerve center
of American capitalism,

1047
00:51:48,692 --> 00:51:52,204
and l realize
what capitalism has done

1048
00:51:52,242 --> 00:51:55,722
for working people in America,
to me that's a holy place.

1049
00:51:55,762 --> 00:51:56,875
Let me add to it.

1050
00:51:56,914 --> 00:52:00,775
Over the whole duration of the lraq war
and the terror war,

1051
00:52:00,818 --> 00:52:04,494
you look at the world's stock markets
and you look at the world economy,

1052
00:52:04,530 --> 00:52:08,326
and despite these horrible pockets
of unrest and killing and murdering

1053
00:52:08,369 --> 00:52:11,150
that we've been describing,
it's never been better.

1054
00:52:11,184 --> 00:52:13,039
The global economy
has never been better

1055
00:52:13,072 --> 00:52:15,592
and the global stock markets
have never been better, Jimmy.

1056
00:52:15,632 --> 00:52:17,574
lt is either a God-given miracle

1057
00:52:17,617 --> 00:52:19,503
or it has something to do
with the victories

1058
00:52:19,536 --> 00:52:21,806
of the spreading world
of capitalism or both.

1059
00:52:21,840 --> 00:52:23,695
Moore: They think
Wall Street's a holy place.

1060
00:52:23,728 --> 00:52:26,543
What do you think
Jesus would think of capitalism?

1061
00:52:26,576 --> 00:52:30,766
l think he would
simply refuse to--

1062
00:52:30,800 --> 00:52:33,903
to be part of it.

1063
00:52:35,023 --> 00:52:37,771
Moore: Jesus would refuse
to be part of it,

1064
00:52:37,806 --> 00:52:39,693
but he probably had
a special place up there

1065
00:52:39,726 --> 00:52:42,541
for whoever leaked
a secret Citibank memo

1066
00:52:42,574 --> 00:52:45,804
about their plan to rule the world.

1067
00:52:45,838 --> 00:52:47,746
Back in 2005 and 2006,

1068
00:52:47,791 --> 00:52:50,027
Citigroup wrote
three confidential memos

1069
00:52:50,061 --> 00:52:54,338
to their wealthiest investors
about how things were going.

1070
00:52:54,382 --> 00:52:56,682
They reached the conclusion
that the United States

1071
00:52:56,717 --> 00:52:58,856
was no longer
really a democracy,

1072
00:52:58,893 --> 00:53:01,543
but had become a plutonomy--

1073
00:53:01,581 --> 00:53:04,547
a society controlled exclusively
by and for the benefit

1074
00:53:04,588 --> 00:53:07,556
of the top 1%
of the population

1075
00:53:07,597 --> 00:53:09,603
who now had
more financial wealth

1076
00:53:09,643 --> 00:53:13,125
than the bottom 95% combined.

1077
00:53:13,164 --> 00:53:16,262
The memo gloated about the growing gap
between rich and poor

1078
00:53:16,300 --> 00:53:19,615
and how they were now
the new aristocracy

1079
00:53:19,659 --> 00:53:23,434
and that there was no end in sight
for the gravy train they were on.

1080
00:53:23,467 --> 00:53:26,882
There was, though,
one problem.

1081
00:53:26,922 --> 00:53:28,385
According to Citigroup,

1082
00:53:28,427 --> 00:53:30,914
the most potent
and short-term threat

1083
00:53:30,954 --> 00:53:32,677
would be societies demanding

1084
00:53:32,715 --> 00:53:35,202
a more equitable share
of the wealth.

1085
00:53:35,242 --> 00:53:39,432
ln other words,
the peasants might revolt.

1086
00:53:39,465 --> 00:53:41,735
Citigroup lamented
that the non-rich

1087
00:53:41,769 --> 00:53:44,135
might not have
much economic power,

1088
00:53:44,170 --> 00:53:47,552
but they do have
equal voting power with the rich.

1089
00:53:47,594 --> 00:53:50,440
One person, one vote.

1090
00:53:50,472 --> 00:53:53,025
And that's what
really scares them--

1091
00:53:53,065 --> 00:53:55,400
that we can still vote.

1092
00:53:55,432 --> 00:53:58,597
ln fact, we have
99% of the votes

1093
00:53:58,632 --> 00:54:01,315
and they only have 1%.

1094
00:54:04,264 --> 00:54:08,061
So why do the 99%
put up with this?

1095
00:54:08,103 --> 00:54:11,398
According to Citigroup,
it's because the majority of the electorate

1096
00:54:11,431 --> 00:54:13,820
believe that someday
they will have a chance

1097
00:54:13,862 --> 00:54:16,284
of becoming
well-to-do themselves

1098
00:54:16,327 --> 00:54:19,360
if they just keep trying
hard enough.

1099
00:54:21,606 --> 00:54:23,811
The wealthy were pleased
that so many people

1100
00:54:23,846 --> 00:54:26,563
had bought in
to the American Dream

1101
00:54:26,597 --> 00:54:29,532
while they, the rich,
had no intention

1102
00:54:29,574 --> 00:54:32,356
of ever sharing it with anyone.

1103
00:54:32,389 --> 00:54:35,552
l think capitalism is a lot more
important than democracy.

1104
00:54:35,590 --> 00:54:37,858
l'm not even a big believer
in democracy.

1105
00:54:37,893 --> 00:54:41,340
l always say that democracy is--
can be two wolves and a sheep

1106
00:54:41,380 --> 00:54:42,974
deciding on what to have
for dinner.

1107
00:54:43,012 --> 00:54:46,110
Moore: This is Stephen Moore--
no relation--

1108
00:54:46,148 --> 00:54:48,483
a columnist
and an editorial board member

1109
00:54:48,516 --> 00:54:50,206
of ''The Wall Street Journal,''

1110
00:54:50,244 --> 00:54:53,539
the daily bible
of corporate America.

1111
00:54:53,572 --> 00:54:56,507
Look, l'm in favor of people
having the right to vote

1112
00:54:56,547 --> 00:54:58,914
and things like that, but you know
there are a lot of countries

1113
00:54:58,947 --> 00:55:02,657
that have the right to vote
that are still poor.

1114
00:55:02,692 --> 00:55:05,920
Democracy doesn't always lead
to a good economy

1115
00:55:05,954 --> 00:55:07,809
or even a good political system.

1116
00:55:07,844 --> 00:55:11,072
With capitalism, you are free
to do what you want,

1117
00:55:11,106 --> 00:55:13,081
to make whatever you want
out of yourself.

1118
00:55:13,123 --> 00:55:14,583
lt doesn't mean
you're gonna succeed.

1119
00:55:14,626 --> 00:55:18,849
Remember, the US Constitution
does not guarantee happiness.

1120
00:55:18,882 --> 00:55:21,402
Moore:
Ah, the Constitution.

1121
00:55:21,442 --> 00:55:25,052
All my life l've heard that America
is a capitalist country.

1122
00:55:25,090 --> 00:55:29,181
So l went to see the original Constitution
and check out if it was true.

1123
00:55:29,217 --> 00:55:32,512
l'm trying to see where it sets up
our economic system,

1124
00:55:32,545 --> 00:55:35,643
like where it says we have
a capitalist economy.

1125
00:55:35,681 --> 00:55:37,753
Guard:
The jurisdiction.

1126
00:55:37,793 --> 00:55:39,516
- Judicial part of the--
- Down there?

1127
00:55:39,552 --> 00:55:43,197
Moore: There was no mention
of free market or free enterprise

1128
00:55:43,231 --> 00:55:45,719
or capitalism anywhere.

1129
00:55:46,719 --> 00:55:49,851
ln fact, all l saw
was ''We the people,''

1130
00:55:49,887 --> 00:55:52,375
something about
''a more perfect union,''

1131
00:55:52,414 --> 00:55:55,643
and ''promoting
the general welfare.''

1132
00:55:55,679 --> 00:55:59,989
Welfare, union, we?

1133
00:56:00,030 --> 00:56:02,333
That sounded like that other -ism.

1134
00:56:02,365 --> 00:56:05,661
But no, that's democracy.

1135
00:56:05,695 --> 00:56:07,326
And l began to wonder,
''What would it be like

1136
00:56:07,326 --> 00:56:08,307
And l began to wonder,
''What would it be like

1137
00:56:08,349 --> 00:56:11,547
if the workplace
was a democracy?''

1138
00:56:11,581 --> 00:56:14,777
There's always been a big separation
between how the country is run

1139
00:56:14,813 --> 00:56:17,911
and how businesses
are supposed to run.

1140
00:56:17,949 --> 00:56:19,094
Moore:
lt's true.

1141
00:56:19,134 --> 00:56:20,922
There seems to be a disconnect

1142
00:56:20,956 --> 00:56:23,193
between our professed love
of democracy

1143
00:56:23,230 --> 00:56:26,130
and how we're so willing
to accept a dictatorship

1144
00:56:26,172 --> 00:56:28,922
every day we show up to work.

1145
00:56:28,956 --> 00:56:32,601
lt's not that way
at lsthmus Engineering in Wisconsin.

1146
00:56:32,635 --> 00:56:36,313
They design and build
robotic machines for industry.

1147
00:56:36,347 --> 00:56:39,382
lt's a $15 million-a-year business.

1148
00:56:39,420 --> 00:56:41,143
Man:
All of the workers

1149
00:56:41,179 --> 00:56:44,376
are the owners of the business.

1150
00:56:44,411 --> 00:56:47,826
Moore: He's not talking about
some bullshit stock option.

1151
00:56:47,867 --> 00:56:51,128
He means they're the true owners.

1152
00:56:51,163 --> 00:56:53,880
Man: And it's a democratically-run
operation where every member

1153
00:56:53,914 --> 00:56:56,762
has one vote and an equal say.

1154
00:56:56,793 --> 00:56:58,965
- All in favor?
- All in favor?

1155
00:56:59,001 --> 00:57:01,903
Man: lt takes the money
out of the equation.

1156
00:57:01,945 --> 00:57:03,887
Moore: By taking the money
out of the equation

1157
00:57:03,929 --> 00:57:06,068
so that they can call the shots,

1158
00:57:06,106 --> 00:57:08,342
they end up making more money.

1159
00:57:08,378 --> 00:57:10,898
Cool, huh?

1160
00:57:14,425 --> 00:57:17,108
And how patriotic
that they want to extend

1161
00:57:17,144 --> 00:57:20,820
their love of American democracy
to their job.

1162
00:57:26,871 --> 00:57:28,726
Just imagine if the place
where you worked

1163
00:57:28,760 --> 00:57:31,793
was run by you
and your fellow workers.

1164
00:57:31,831 --> 00:57:33,621
You probably wouldn't
lay off your coworkers

1165
00:57:33,655 --> 00:57:36,471
to increase the value
of your stock, would you?

1166
00:57:36,503 --> 00:57:37,909
Or give yourself
a pay raise

1167
00:57:37,943 --> 00:57:40,693
while making your coworkers
take a pay cut.

1168
00:57:40,726 --> 00:57:42,516
Man:
We don't really do that here.

1169
00:57:42,550 --> 00:57:45,998
You really can't because everyone else
would be looking at you

1170
00:57:46,038 --> 00:57:48,492
saying, ''Why is this guy
so fricking greedy?''

1171
00:57:48,534 --> 00:57:51,021
You know,
it would be too obvious.

1172
00:57:51,061 --> 00:57:52,851
The bottom line is you've
got plenty of people

1173
00:57:52,885 --> 00:57:54,608
who roll up their sleeves
every day and go to work.

1174
00:57:54,646 --> 00:57:56,467
But if there's someone
way up there on the chain

1175
00:57:56,501 --> 00:57:59,402
that collects all the extra money,
that's not fair.

1176
00:57:59,445 --> 00:58:03,056
Moore:
Huh, fairness in the workplace--

1177
00:58:03,092 --> 00:58:05,329
what a novel idea.

1178
00:58:06,708 --> 00:58:09,806
Out in California,
there's a bread factory

1179
00:58:09,844 --> 00:58:13,259
where workers make thousands
of loaves of bread every day

1180
00:58:13,300 --> 00:58:15,210
Man:
The more hours you work towards

1181
00:58:15,251 --> 00:58:16,496
the benefit
of the co-op,

1182
00:58:16,532 --> 00:58:19,282
the more you share
in the profits.

1183
00:58:19,315 --> 00:58:21,420
Man #2:
The workers are happy here.

1184
00:58:21,458 --> 00:58:23,826
No big ls, little yous.
Everyone's the same.

1185
00:58:23,860 --> 00:58:27,208
Me as the CEO,
l get the same share

1186
00:58:27,251 --> 00:58:29,193
that anybody else does.

1187
00:58:29,235 --> 00:58:30,958
And that has proven

1188
00:58:30,994 --> 00:58:33,231
to be very lucrative
for us as workers.

1189
00:58:34,994 --> 00:58:39,369
Moore: Assembly-line workers here
earn over $65,000 a year,

1190
00:58:39,409 --> 00:58:41,416
more than
three times the pay

1191
00:58:41,458 --> 00:58:43,914
for a starting pilot
at American Eagle.

1192
00:58:43,954 --> 00:58:46,637
Man: l'm just hoping
that people take notice

1193
00:58:46,673 --> 00:58:48,746
of this type
of organizational activity

1194
00:58:48,784 --> 00:58:52,047
and start considering it
as an alternative.

1195
00:58:52,081 --> 00:58:53,358
Why do you want
to get rich?

1196
00:58:53,393 --> 00:58:55,248
How many cars do
you really need in life?

1197
00:58:55,280 --> 00:58:59,688
Moore: Clearly, he's not a car guy,
but that's okay.

1198
00:58:59,728 --> 00:59:03,110
His bread factory and hundreds of other
worker-owned businesses

1199
00:59:03,152 --> 00:59:06,599
are proof that people aren't always
motivated by profit.

1200
00:59:06,639 --> 00:59:09,322
( fanfare )

1201
00:59:09,360 --> 00:59:11,880
Announcer:
An historic victory over a dread disease.

1202
00:59:11,920 --> 00:59:15,148
Moore: lnstead of using his genius
to make a ton of money,

1203
00:59:15,184 --> 00:59:18,315
Dr. Jonas Salk spent
all of his time

1204
00:59:18,351 --> 00:59:20,739
putting monkey kidneys
in a blender

1205
00:59:20,782 --> 00:59:22,757
trying to find a cure
for polio.

1206
00:59:22,798 --> 00:59:27,467
And when he did,
he decided to give it away for free.

1207
00:59:27,501 --> 00:59:30,436
This man could have been rich
many times over

1208
00:59:30,478 --> 00:59:33,673
had he sold his vaccine
to a pharmaceutical company.

1209
00:59:33,710 --> 00:59:36,043
But he thought
his talents should be used

1210
00:59:36,077 --> 00:59:37,222
for the greater good.

1211
00:59:37,262 --> 00:59:40,076
And the decent salary
he made as a doctor

1212
00:59:40,110 --> 00:59:42,411
and a research professor
was enough for him to live

1213
00:59:42,445 --> 00:59:44,418
a comfortable life.

1214
00:59:44,460 --> 00:59:46,762
Who owns the patent
on this vaccine?

1215
